AN INGENIOUS INVENTION: A NEW FOOT CYCLE.  The illustrations of a foot cycle given above arc taken from the Leader, and will be of cons derable interest to the public, as the new device promises to create an epoch in the cycle woild. The inventor of the cycle is Mr Henry Glade, a resident of Mclbourre, and the scries of pictures which -we present show the inventor in action on the roof of Broken Hill Chambers, overlooking the city. The ease and grace ■with which the cycle can be ridden will at once be observed. The weight of the rider's body is the sole motive power required, and a speed of 14 miles an hour can be ridden with ease ever rough tracks or gutters. Mr Glade has given demonstrations in Me1 bourne of his new machine, and the inventor will be observed in a mackintosh, holding his umbrella over his head He will also be seen stooping from the cycle to pick a coin from the ground. Another view is given in whish Mr Geo. B. Gordon, of Queen street, the secretary of the Glade Cycle Company, is wrestling with the inventor on his cycle; while other illustrations show the rider standing and moving rapidly in characteristic action. The new machine can be easily ridden by ladies, for the skirts can in no way hinder the speed of the cycle (Otago Witness, 20 July 1904)
